From: lxh <lmhtq1991@gmail.com>
Date: Thu, 28 May 2026 14:30:00 +0800
Subject: [PATCH] Phase C-6 fix #10: set bit 0 on stub function pointer for C64 mode

Per the Morello ARM ARM (DDI0606 §2.10):

  RZRMXS: PSTATE.C64 determines the current instruction set:
            PSTATE.C64 = 0: A64 mode
            PSTATE.C64 = 1: C64 mode
  RZTMWK: PSTATE.C64 is updated by the Capability Value[0] of a
            branch with a capability target.

I.e., on BLR <Cd>, the new PSTATE.C64 = Cd.address & 1 (the low bit
of the cap's address). This is analogous to ARM/Thumb interworking
on AArch32 (the Thumb-mode bit on function pointers).

HotSpot's `__ pc()` returns the raw, byte-aligned PC value with bit
0 = 0. When `StubRoutines::_call_stub_entry` is assigned this value
and later invoked via BLR (in JavaCalls::call_helper at the
`StubRoutines::call_stub()(...)` call site), the BLR sees Cd's bit
0 = 0 and sets PSTATE.C64 = 0 → CPU enters A64 mode. But the stub's
emitted bytes are C64-format (e.g., cap-STP 0x62BF7BFD, cap-ADD
0x020003FD, etc.). The CPU mis-interprets them in A64 mode and
faults — observed as PROT_CHERI_TAG on ifetch at the very first
stub byte.

Diagnostic from the cap_runtime SIGPROT handler with bounds+flags
dump confirmed this: `PCC flags=0` at fault time, where bit 0 of
the cap flags reflects PSTATE.C64. flags=0 = A64 mode, exactly
matching the BLR target's bit 0.

Fix: in JavaCalls::call_helper, OR bit 0 into the call_stub cap
address before invoking. Use __builtin_cheri_address_set to
preserve the cap's tag/bounds/permissions/flags while changing
just the address.

Verified by the diagnostic: after the patch, the BLR target prints
as 0x428b8139 (bit 0 = 1, C64 mode). The crash mode changes from
PROT_CHERI_TAG (signal 34, exit 162) to SIGILL (signal 4, exit 132),
meaning the CPU now enters C64 mode and successfully executes the
cap-stp + cap-add prologue, but hits an illegal instruction farther
into call_stub. That's the next layer (likely another emitter
that's still emitting an integer-only encoding).

Scope note: this is a SPOT FIX at the one call site. A proper fix
would have the stub generator OR bit 0 into the address before
storing into _call_stub_entry (and all other stub entry pointers).
The spot fix unblocks the immediate path; the systematic fix lands
in C-13.

diff --git a/src/hotspot/share/runtime/javaCalls.cpp b/src/hotspot/share/runtime/javaCalls.cpp
--- a/src/hotspot/share/runtime/javaCalls.cpp
+++ b/src/hotspot/share/runtime/javaCalls.cpp
@@ -426,9 +426,27 @@
       }
 #endif
+#ifdef __CHERI_PURE_CAPABILITY__
+      // C-6 fix #10: on Morello, BLR to a capability target sets
+      // PSTATE.C64 = target_cap.Value[0]. Our generated stubs are
+      // C64-mode code but the cap returned by StubRoutines::call_stub()
+      // has address 0x...8 (bit 0 = 0), so BLR enters A64 mode and
+      // misinterprets the C64 encoding → CAP_TAG fault on ifetch.
+      // (ARM ARM DDI0606 §2.10 RZTMWK + RZRMXS.) Fix: OR bit 0 into
+      // the cap address before invoking, preserving tag/bounds/perms.
+      StubRoutines::CallStub _cs = StubRoutines::call_stub();
+      void* _cs_v = (void*)_cs;
+      unsigned long _cs_addr = (unsigned long)__builtin_cheri_address_get(_cs_v);
+      _cs_v = __builtin_cheri_address_set(_cs_v, _cs_addr | 1);
+      ((StubRoutines::CallStub)_cs_v)(
+        (address)&link,
+#else
       StubRoutines::call_stub()(
         (address)&link,
+#endif
         result_val_address,          // see NOTE above (compiler problem)
         result_type,
         method(),
